KW  - business cycles
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-2879
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.12373
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - The paper proposes endogenous information choice as a channel through which uncertainty affects price dynamics. I consider a rational inattention model with volatility uncertainty and endogenous information processing capability. According to the model, firms' learning and optimal attention exhibits inertia and asymmetry in response to volatility changes. Firms choose to process more information when uncertainty rises, especially about aggregate conditions, and their pricing behavior changes accordingly. Using a Markov-switching factor-augmented vector autoregression (MS-FAVAR), the paper also documents a significant positive correlation between volatility and firms' responsiveness to macro- and microlevel shocks, consistent with model predictions.
ER  - 

